## Why not say something sooner?

I've had bad experiences; coming out to those close to me damaged a few relationships.

I had enough stress to deal with starting a new high-pressure job, and I (wrongly) figured it would make little difference to me which name I went by. I'm from a small rural town where homophobia and bigotry were defaults, so I tend to be a bit pessimistic about people's social attitudes. I was worried that a fraction of people would react badly, or I'd end up in some sort of exhausting battle for respectful treatment at work. I'm not a person who enjoys conflict.

There's never a good time to come out, though now is better than later. I trust that the people I work with are decent & will stay easy to work with.

## What changes?

Not much, ideally. I've had a range of responses from those close to me, my favourite of which by far was from a friend who uses my new name & pronouns and was otherwise fairly disinterested.

I really don't mind if people occasionally slip up names/pronouns, especially in the near future. I have known people who "slipped up" in [bad faith](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bad_faith), so please don't do that, I find _that_ personally insulting.

Beyond my name & pronouns, I don't really expect anything to change. I find this topic extraordinarily disconcerting to talk about, so generally I'd rather not. In particular, I don't want to respond to wedge-issue "debates" repeated ad nauseum online or justify trans people's basic rights.

